    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>It's because server is listening to 5000, Adding \"server.port=5000\" to application.properties fixed the issue.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 14033780,
      "reputation" : 317,
      "user_id" : 10136948,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f073dfd5441ec81bb681120025c15367?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "som3_l0cust",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/10136948/som3-l0cust"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1603418429,
    "creation_date" : 1603418429,
    "answer_id" : 64492850,
    "question_id" : 54612962,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>My issue was my <code>Java</code> version didn't match the platform I'm running with Elastic Beanstalk, even tho my <code>server.port</code> was on <code>5000</code>. My Java version was 11, and my platform was only Java 8 for Amazon Linux. So changing it to 8 in my base <code>pom.xml</code> fixed it.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 14493854,
        "reputation" : 1069,
        "user_id" : 10529573,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fd97a51e722de8be211009110b09f13f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
